Alan Fozo Service Center Manager called safety to report report evidence of a spill in trailer 84740, UN1648, ACETONITRILE 3 PG II. 1 Gallon pail. Alan stated when the crew opened the trailer door on the trailer and started to unload, they found a box that looked to have been forked by a forklift. A lan stated the only evidence of the spill was the hole in the box and a damaged 1 gallon pail in the box that was dry. Alan stated it looks like the ACETONITRILE had evaporated and left no trace of the spill. Alan stated he was going to take the damaged pail and place it in a recovery pail with Pro Number in OSD. Alan stated after removing the pallet and the box from the skid, there was no spill to be cleaned other than a damaged glass pail in the box.  Alan stated the box that was damaged by the forklift blade was done at the loading facility and found the damaged box at SC 106 in trailer 847 40 while unloading.
column170: Refresher training on loading and unloading freight in a safe practice.

On October 1, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN3077 was damaged by a forklift and released approximately sixteen (16) ounces of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EX Environmental (EXE) to remediate the site. EXE personnel utilized a vacuum unit to remediate the UN3077-impacted trailer. The unaffected freight was restacked and rewrapped onsite for future terminal use. All waste was collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum which was staged onsite for future disposal.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal XNA experienced a UN2735 Baxxodur EC301 release from a 55-gallon metal drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 30-gallons of Baxxodur EC301 released to a 100’ x 20’ area of the asphalt lot and a 15’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor. The drum was punctured by a metal plate which slid within the trailer during transport. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon poly overpack. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted areas to clean the release. The impacted absorbents were containerized into a 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was removed from site for disposal.
The pail was punctured by a pail on the pallet.
column170: Ensure all freight is properly secured.

column169: On October 2, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN3267 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Works, Inc. (EWI) to remediate the impacted site. EWI personnel utilized hand tools, absorbents, and soda ash to remediate the UN3267-impacted impacted dock floor. EWI personnel patch the 55-gallon drum of UN3267, and containerized it in one (1) 95-gallon poly over-pack and staged onsite. All impacted debris was collected and containerized one (1) 55-gallon drum  and staged onsite.

XPO Logistics terminal XTM experienced a UN3266 PI-2100 release from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 55-gallons of product released to a 15’ x 20’ area of the concrete dock floor. Prior to their arrival, XPO placed wood chips and absorbents down to contain the release. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon poly overpack. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted area. All impacted absorbents, wood chips, cleanup debris, and the impacted pallet were containerized into 2 flex bins and (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On 10/2/2024 at approximately 1245, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 393838 at the ramp facility in Fort Worth,  reporting a dangerous goods spill.  The shipment consisted of one fiberboard box that contained 4 glass bottles of petroleum crude oil.  The package was damaged by mechanical equipment, resulting in one of the glass bottles breaking and spilling.   There is no secondary containment or positive closure.  The cushioning between the bottles was insufficient.  The broken glass and damaged outer package were placed in a salvage drum for proper disposal and the remaining bottles were placed in a separate drum, awaiting an amended Shipper's Declaration for futher transport.

XPO Logistics terminal XHG experienced a UN3082 Surfonic JL-80X release from a 55-gallon metal drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 5-gallons of product released to a 4’ x 4’ area of the trailer floor, and a 15' x 8' area of the concrete lot below. The drum was punctured by a forklift. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon metal overpack. Absorbents were then deployed and worked into the impacted area. The impacted absorbents were then containerized into a 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On October 1, 2024, six (6) one-gallon pails of paint were damaged by a forklift and released approximately four (4) gallons of paint to the trailer interior, dock floor, and pavement. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the UN1263-impacted trailer, dock, and pavement and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum, and four (4) 1-gallon pails of UN1263 were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal.

column169: On 10/6/2024 at approximately 2300, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Hub Security in Indianapolis, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of 4 wooden pallets, each supporting a large fiberboard gaylords, containing used cell phones and cell phone batteries.  The shipment was discovered by security after collapsing under the weight of the inner contents, revealing the cell phones.  The shipments were not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations,  missing the required markings, labeling, and paperwork.  The shipment was held for the FAA investigation.

XPO Logistics contacted ERTS regarding the release of hazardous product, WRXSOL-ECO-CR from a 330-gallon tote. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 10-gallon release from a crack in the tote that impacted the inside of the trailer (floors and walls) in a 10’x8.5’ area. The contractor neutralized the impacted area using backing soda and performed a tote transfer. The damaged tote was neutralized and taken for disposal by the Contractor. No other waste was generated from this response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

column169: Undeclared Hazmat found with a strong odor of gasoline emitting from the package. On further inspection, found a used Sencore Handheld Saw that is gas powered inside. On opening the gas cap found that there was gas left inside the tank. Did not find any leakage of gas from around the cap and cap is not loose when secured. Could not find leakage of gas but there is still a strong gas fume coming from the saw when gas cap is secure.  Note: Could not find specs for the specific hand saw. Found specs on a different gas-powered handsaw for section 15a "Inner Material" capacity.  Actual gas tank capacity unknown as well as amount shipped inside the handsaw. Tank did not appear full on inspection. Provided SDS for all grades of gasoline since type used is unknown.  15a. Number in Shipment: 1

column169: On October 2, 2024, two (2) 1.5 gallon jugs of hydrogen peroxide were damaged by a forklift and released approximately three (3) gallons of product to the trailer interior and dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. AT THE UPS WORLDPORT FACILITY IN LOUISVILLE KENTUCKY, ONE AIR PACKAGE WITH A GROUND LIMITED QUANTITY MARKING WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING TRAILER UNLOAD. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS THERE ARE THIRTY-FIVE VARIOUS PERFUMES AND COLOGNES SURROUNDED BY FOAM WRAPPING INSIDE THE BOX. THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY A SINGLE 125 ML BOTTLE OF DIESEL FUEL FOR LIFE COLOGNE BEING SHATTERED. THE GROUND LIMITED QUANTITY MARKING IS THE ONLY DANGEROUS GOODS INDICATOR ON THE PACKAGE. THIS PACKAGE HAS NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO.

On October 10, 2024, at 1154 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Euclid, OH regarding the release of Paraformaldehyde Prills 91-93%. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 150 lbs of Paraformaldehyde Prills 91-93% (UN2213, 4.1, III) from (3) bags onto the trailer floor. The release was reportedly due to impact from pallets during loading, affecting multiple areas in the trailer. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The contractors collected the release with the proper PPE. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (2) 55-gallon DF, which were then taken off site by contractors for proper disposal.

On October 3, 2024, one (1) 50-pound bag of UN1823 was torn during unloading and released approximately two (2) pounds of product to the loading dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) to remediate the impacted site. HES deployed and absorbents and utilized hand tools to remediate the area. All impacted debris was collected and containerized into one (1) 5-gallon bucket for disposal. HES removed the one (1) damaged bag of sodium hydroxide powder and placed it into a 55-gallon drum for disposal.

column169: On October 4th during the PM sort a package was discovered that had a distinct sound of an aerosol can.   After calling DG Admin the station opened the package and found three cans of spray paint. There are no markings or labels on the outside of the package that indicates the package contains any dangerous goods, however a safety data sheet classifies these as UN1950, Aerosols, flammable, 2.1.  The package is being help pending investigation of the FAA.
